    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN177.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">piriviṭai vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷait tōḻi vaṟpuṟīiyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">How the confidante consoled HER who had undergone changes in the time of separation.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN177.2">
      <lg type="edition">
        <l>toṉṉalañ citaiyac cā<supplied>a</supplied> yalkalu</l>
        <l>miṉṉum vārā riṉiyevaṉ ceykeṉap</l>
        <l>perumpulam puṟuta lōmpumati ciṟuka</l>
        <l>ṇirumpiṭit taṭakkai yiṉmāṉ neyyarun</l>
        <l>toruṅkupiṇit tiyaṉṟa veṟiko ḷaimpāṟ</l>
        <l>ṟēṅkamaḻ veṟimalar peymmār kāṇpiṉ</l>
        <l>kaḻaiyamal cilampiṉ vaḻaitalai vāṭak</l>
        <l>katirkataṅ kaṟṟa vēka ṉeṟiyiṭaip</l>
        <l>paiṅkoṭip pākaṟ ceṅka<supplied>ṉi</supplied> nacaiik</l>
        <l>kāṉa maññaik kamañcūṉ māppeṭai</l>
        <l>yayiryāṟ ṟaṭaikarai vayiri ṉaraluṅ</l>
        <l>kāṭiṟan takaṉṟōr nīṭiṉa rāyiṉum</l>
        <l>vallē varuvar pōlum veṉvē</l>
        <l>lilainiṟam peyara vōcci māṟṟōr</l>
        <l>malaimaruḷ yāṉai māṇṭama roḻitta</l>
        <l>kaḻaṟkāṟ paṇṇaṉ kāviri vaṭa<supplied>va</supplied>yi</l>
        <l>ṉiḻaṟkayan taḻīiya neṭuṅkāṉ māviṉ</l>
        <l>ṟaḷirē rākan takaipeṟa mukainta</l>
        <l>vaṇaṅkuṭai vaṉamulait tāayaniṉ</l>
        <l>cuṇaṅkiṭai varitta toyyilai niṉaintē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        <l>“Exhausted so that [my] old beauty is spoiled, all night, (1)</l>
        <l>even now he does not come. Now, what will I do?”, saying so, (2)</l>
        <l>beware of feeling great loneliness! (3a-c)</l>
        <l>In order to put perfumed blossoms smelling of honey (6a-c)</l>
        <l>in [your] perfumed [hair in] five parts that was made up by tying [it] together, (5)</l>
        <l>absorbing oil, resembling the broad trunk of the small-eyed dark she-elephant, (3df.)</l>
        <l>he who departed traversing the wilderness, (12ab)</l>
        <l>where, on the path of ample stones that has learned the [sun] rays’ anger (8)</l>
        <l>when the tops of the gamboge faded on the mountain side thickly grown with bamboo pleasing to see, (6df.)</l>
        <l>the fully pregnant dark female of the forest peacock, (10)</l>
        <l>yearning for the red fruit of the Pākal in fresh creepers, (9)</l>
        <l>calls out like a bugle on the setting shore of the shining river (11)</l>
        <l rend="indent8">even if he is delayed, (12cd)</l>
        <l>he will come [back] quickly, it seems, (13a-c)</l>
        <l>– thinking of the sandel paste drawn on your waist with beauty spots (20)</l>
        <l>that spread up to the tormenting beautiful breasts (19)</l>
        <l>that budded befittingly on [your] bosom that resembles [in colour] the sprouts (18)</l>
        <l>of the large-trunked mango tree that embraces the shady pond (17)</l>
        <l>on the northern side of the Kāviri of Paṇṇaṉ, with anklets on [his] legs, (16)</l>
        <l>who gloriously ended the battle with the mountain-like elephants (15)</l>
        <l>of the enemies, raising [his] victorious spear</l>
        <l rend="indent8">so that [it] leaf[-shaped] tip moves into the vital spot. (13df.)</l>
      </lg>
        </div>
